 {"id":"remote_compilation_helper-edn","title":"Network Benchmark Implementation (Rust-Native)","description":"## Overview
Implement a network throughput and latency benchmark to measure worker network performance for data transfer operations critical to remote compilation.

## Background and Justification
Remote compilation requires transferring:
- Source files and dependencies TO the worker
- Compiled artifacts (binaries, object files) FROM the worker
- Incremental compilation caches in both directions

Network performance directly impacts total compilation time. A worker with excellent CPU but poor network may be slower overall than a moderate CPU worker with excellent network connectivity.

## Architecture: SSH-Based Network Testing

### Challenge
RCH uses daemon-initiated SSH connections. Workers don't maintain persistent connections and may be behind NAT. A traditional push-based network test (worker connects to daemon) may not work.

### Solution: Bidirectional SSH Transfer Test
Instead of a separate network test server, we measure actual rsync-like transfer performance through SSH - which is the real workload.

\`\`\`
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                        Network Benchmark                         │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                                                                  │
│   1. Generate test payload on daemon (random data)               │
│      └── /tmp/rch_bench_upload_XXXX (10MB)                      │
│                                                                  │
│   2. SSH+rsync TO worker (upload test)                          │
│      ┌──────┐    rsync --progress    ┌──────┐                   │
│      │daemon│ ────────────────────▶  │worker│                   │
│      └──────┘                        └──────┘                   │
│      └── Measure: bytes/time = upload_mbps                      │
│                                                                  │
│   3. SSH+rsync FROM worker (download test)                      │
│      ┌──────┐    rsync --progress    ┌──────┐                   │
│      │daemon│ ◀────────────────────  │worker│                   │
│      └──────┘                        └──────┘                   │
│      └── Measure: bytes/time = download_mbps                    │
│                                                                  │
│   4. SSH latency (round-trip time)                              │
│      └── Measure: ssh worker 'echo ping' × 10 iterations        │
│                                                                  │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
\`\`\`

## Implementation Details

### Network Benchmark Structure
\`\`\`rust
pub struct NetworkBenchmark {
    worker: WorkerConfig,
    payload_size_mb: usize,     // Default: 10 MB
    latency_samples: usize,     // Default: 10
    ssh_options: SshOptions,
}

pub struct NetworkResult {
    pub upload_mbps: f64,
    pub download_mbps: f64,
    pub latency_ms: f64,
    pub jitter_ms: f64,
    pub ssh_version: String,
}
\`\`\`

### Benchmark Implementation
\`\`\`rust
use std::process::Command;
use std::time::Instant;
use tempfile::NamedTempFile;

impl NetworkBenchmark {
    pub async fn run(&self) -> Result<NetworkResult> {
        info!(worker = %self.worker.id, "Starting network benchmark");

        // Step 1: Generate test payload
        let payload = self.generate_test_payload()?;
        debug!(size_mb = self.payload_size_mb, "Generated test payload");

        // Step 2: Upload test (daemon → worker)
        let upload_mbps = self.measure_upload(&payload).await?;
        info!(upload_mbps = %upload_mbps, "Upload test complete");

        // Step 3: Download test (worker → daemon)
        let download_mbps = self.measure_download().await?;
        info!(download_mbps = %download_mbps, "Download test complete");

        // Step 4: Latency test
        let (latency_ms, jitter_ms) = self.measure_latency().await?;
        info!(latency_ms = %latency_ms, jitter_ms = %jitter_ms, "Latency test complete");

        // Cleanup
        self.cleanup_remote().await?;

        Ok(NetworkResult {
            upload_mbps,
            download_mbps,
            latency_ms,
            jitter_ms,
            ssh_version: self.get_ssh_version()?,
        })
    }

    fn generate_test_payload(&self) -> Result<NamedTempFile> {
        let mut file = NamedTempFile::new()?;
        let size_bytes = self.payload_size_mb * 1024 * 1024;

        // Generate random data (use fast PRNG, not crypto)
        let mut rng = fastrand::Rng::new();
        let mut buffer = vec![0u8; 65536];
        let mut written = 0usize;

        while written < size_bytes {
            rng.fill(&mut buffer);
            let to_write = (size_bytes - written).min(buffer.len());
            file.write_all(&buffer[..to_write])?;
            written += to_write;
        }

        file.flush()?;
        Ok(file)
    }

    async fn measure_upload(&self, payload: &Path) -> Result<f64> {
        let remote_path = format!("/tmp/rch_netbench_{}", self.worker.id);

        let start = Instant::now();

        // Use rsync with compression disabled for accurate bandwidth measurement
        let status = Command::new("rsync")
            .args([
                "-e", &format!("ssh -o BatchMode=yes -i {}", self.worker.identity_file),
                "--progress",
                "--compress-level=0",  // No compression
                payload.to_str().unwrap(),
                &format!("{}@{}:{}", self.worker.user, self.worker.host, remote_path),
            ])
            .output()
            .await?;

        let duration = start.elapsed();

        if !status.status.success() {
            anyhow::bail!("Upload failed: {}", String::from_utf8_lossy(&status.stderr));
        }

        let bytes = std::fs::metadata(payload)?.len() as f64;
        let mbps = (bytes * 8.0) / duration.as_secs_f64() / 1_000_000.0;

        Ok(mbps)
    }

    async fn measure_download(&self) -> Result<f64> {
        let remote_path = format!("/tmp/rch_netbench_{}", self.worker.id);
        let local_temp = NamedTempFile::new()?;

        let start = Instant::now();

        let status = Command::new("rsync")
            .args([
                "-e", &format!("ssh -o BatchMode=yes -i {}", self.worker.identity_file),
                "--progress",
                "--compress-level=0",
                &format!("{}@{}:{}", self.worker.user, self.worker.host, remote_path),
                local_temp.path().to_str().unwrap(),
            ])
            .output()
            .await?;

        let duration = start.elapsed();

        if !status.status.success() {
            anyhow::bail!("Download failed: {}", String::from_utf8_lossy(&status.stderr));
        }

        let bytes = std::fs::metadata(local_temp.path())?.len() as f64;
        let mbps = (bytes * 8.0) / duration.as_secs_f64() / 1_000_000.0;

        Ok(mbps)
    }

    async fn measure_latency(&self) -> Result<(f64, f64)> {
        let mut latencies = Vec::with_capacity(self.latency_samples);

        for i in 0..self.latency_samples {
            let start = Instant::now();

            let status = Command::new("ssh")
                .args([
                    "-o", "BatchMode=yes",
                    "-i", &self.worker.identity_file,
                    &format!("{}@{}", self.worker.user, self.worker.host),
                    "echo", "ping",
                ])
                .output()
                .await?;

            let latency = start.elapsed().as_secs_f64() * 1000.0;

            if status.status.success() {
                latencies.push(latency);
                trace!(sample = i, latency_ms = %latency, "Latency sample");
            }
        }

        if latencies.is_empty() {
            anyhow::bail!("All latency samples failed");
        }

        // Calculate median and jitter (std dev)
        latencies.sort_by(|a, b| a.partial_cmp(b).unwrap());
        let median = latencies[latencies.len() / 2];

        let mean = latencies.iter().sum::<f64>() / latencies.len() as f64;
        let variance = latencies.iter()
            .map(|l| (l - mean).powi(2))
            .sum::<f64>() / latencies.len() as f64;
        let jitter = variance.sqrt();

        Ok((median, jitter))
    }

    async fn cleanup_remote(&self) -> Result<()> {
        let remote_path = format!("/tmp/rch_netbench_{}", self.worker.id);

        Command::new("ssh")
            .args([
                "-o", "BatchMode=yes",
                "-i", &self.worker.identity_file,
                &format!("{}@{}", self.worker.user, self.worker.host),
                "rm", "-f", &remote_path,
            ])
            .output()
            .await?;

        Ok(())
    }
}
